name: Mitsuro Hikime Japanese Wax Class
description:
Mitsuro Hikime is an ancient Japanese wax technique dating back to 460 AD, an art that was almost lost to history.  
  
Mitso (honey) ro (wax)  hiki (drawing)  me (texture)

The technique is based on a recipe of pine resin and wax that develops a taffy like texture, and unlike other wax techniques that are rigid and require carving and sculpting, Mitsuro wax is stretched, pulled, and manipulated.  A successful result should have beautiful ridges and lines, meant to mimic the natural fibrous grooves of the bamboo leaf.  

This process requires free thinking, a flexible spirit and the willingness to play.  Mitsuro is like sketching.  It is fluid and requires being in the moment and adjusting quickly to how the wax moves and responds.  It is delightfully spontaneous and freeing for those who dare to try.

Students will spend the class learning about the history of Mitsuro, learn the very special previously unrecorded recipe (generously provided by Susan Zeiss of Tacoma Washington who has been a leader in the American Revival of Mitsuro Hikime), and will spend the bulk of the time in class 'sketching' with the wax.  Most students will produce many items, and will at the end of class have time to reflect on which should be casted into a bronze or silver finished piece of jewelry to be picked up at a later date.

Students will leave class with a prepared batch of the wax recipe so that going home and getting started will be simple and effortless.  We also provide you with resources on how to get started--including where to buy your supplies, how to hire someone to cast your designs for you, and how to further your education. 

LEVEL: Beginner to advanced

name: Sawing Class
description:
One of the essential tools in any jeweler's toolbox is the jeweler's saw. The saw is used to cut metal into various shapes, and this simple skill will expand the horizons of what is possible.  You will learn how to cut different metals in straight lines, curves, circles, and how to cut the interior out of a metal sheet.  

If you have experience with beading or assembling jewelry with store bought components, this class is totally freeing, as you will learn how to design and cut your own components, making your work that much more your own, reflecting your unique voice in the world.

Students will spend the class learning the basics of how to use a jeweler's saw, as well as how to sketch and transfer designs to metal, how to drill, file, sand, and finish a design so that it is ready to wear.  Students will make a pendant, earrings, or charm in class in brass or copper and will leave with a finished piece of jewelry.

Our guiding principle for the class is to introduce students to jewelry making concepts and processes with tools you may already have in your garage to make custom jewelry. We want to introduce you to this craft without pressuring you to buy lots of tools and product; but if you do fall in love with jewelry making, we also provide you with you resources on how to get started--including where to buy your supplies and how to further your education.
